   On adapting literary works to music and rewriting Edgar Allan Poe’s
   poetry in his 2003 album The Raven and the companion graphic novel:

   IFRAME:
   https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/track
   s/119647236&auto_play=false&hide_related=false&visual=true

     The trouble with Poe was that his language is so serious — the
     vocabulary — the words he’s using — some of those words were arcane
     when he used them — and then, architectural terms from Greece. And
     I, dutifully sitting there with the dictionary, looking all of this
     up and thinking, certainly, in a song or on the album I don’t want
     to have [things like this] in there — you can just as easily use a
     word someone knows what it means. … For him, great. For me, no. I
     spent most of the time translating them into English before even
     starting, but I couldn’t wait to rewrite “The Raven,” the poem. Mine
     is like a contemporary version of it, and we have a graphic novel
     out … illustrated by this great Italian artist, Lorenzo Mattotti. …
     Making things that are beautiful is real fun.

